PSY T880 Course Project: Kaggle House Prices Challenge

Introduction to the Challenge

This course project is taken from the Kaggle competition:

House Prices: Advanced Regression Techniques

A lot of very talented Kagglers have already submitted their solutions, and so I’ll be sure to reference them whenever possible.

The model will be validated by the test set RMSE between \(log(y)\) and \(log(\hat y)\).

First, we will explore the data set to see what we have.

We have the variable descriptions in a text file provided by the competition. Our outcome variable is “SalePrice”. We can start our data investigation here.

Acknowledgement: Comprehensive data exploration is highly recommended for data scientists, but there really isn’t a formal accepted school of thought on what that means. Pedro Marcelino produced a very thorough analysis of variables in his kernel here.

Comprehensive Data Exploration

The aim here is to best understand the distributions, relationships, and any erroneous qualities of the variables. This is seperate from data cleaning (as you can’t clean a room you’re not familiar with).

Marcelino, in his kernel, recommends that a thorough analysis involve the following:

  1. Understanding the problem and the variables
  2. Univariate study of the outcome variable
  3. Multivariate study of the predictors/features
  4. Cleaning
  5. Checking of assumptions

So we’ll start at the beginning: Understanding the problem.

Understanding the Problem

From the data set, it’s clear that real estate data can be a very granular and complex problem. However, even with all the granularity you could bring to measuring every quality of a property, at the end of the day, a human being is going to make a subjective judgment on whether or not they “like” the property. So when it comes to the binary decision of sell or not sell, the data set has to somehow mimic that property. Fortunately, we are not predicting a sale, but the Sale Price. This means that we can use the quantitative and more objective values, but we would still need to consider that there will be some subjective measurements that would push demand and supply for property; this can’t be avoided, and so my own intuition is to put increased weight on what could be thought of as cognitive decision-based features.

I’m calling this the behaviorist’s perspective to data analysis, although I’m sure it’s more appropriate to just call this “domain knowledge”. It’ll help us to make sure to incorporate some of the behavioral tendencies of people in our approach to predicting Sale Price.

The features themselves are very many, and some are quite related. I’ve tried to group the related variables in the lists below:

Type_of_property = c("MSSubClass", "MSZoning", "LotShape", "LotConfig", "Condition1", "Condition2", "BldgType", "HouseStyle", "GarageType", "SaleType", "MoSold", "YrSold", 'SaleCondition')
Geographic_qualities = c("LandContour", "LandSlope", "Neighborhood")

The Outcome: SalesPrice

Let’s start by simply visualising the variable.

hist(train$SalePrice[1:train_index], breaks = 100)

With this level of breaks, there is a clear skew with this variable. It has a heavy right tail. We can check just how skewed this is:

skewness(train$SalePrice[1:train_index])
[1] 1.879009
kurtosis(train$SalePrice[1:train_index])
[1] 6.496789

It’s relatively skewed, but not obscenely non-normal. This problem might therefore lend itself to a non-linear prediction method, but linear methods may perform relatively well. Alternately, we can see if outliers tell us more about the data.

boxplot(train$SalePrice[1:train_index])

From this plot, it’s clear that there are a number of statistical outliers, but all on the right end of the distribution. Like above, this is not a case where deleting outliers would help.

hist(log(train$SalePrice[1:train_index]), breaks = 100)

boxplot(log(train$SalePrice[1:train_index]))

With these plots, we can see that log-transforming the outcome variable creates a distribution that is far more normal and has outliers on either end of the range; it would be worth investigating whether or not the outliers are represented significantly in any particular variables (such as whether they are mansions or penthouses of some kind).

Missing Data & Needless Variables

Missing data can be problematic, and we usually deal with it by removing rows with incomplete data. With this many variables, it might be useful to cut down on the implications by just taking out any variables that are probably not going to tell us anything and not be useful in the regression problem. A useful way to do this is to see how many missing values might be in each variable and delete those that contribute too much missingness.

To start off, only 81 houses (6%) don’t have garages. I feel like this would significantly reduce the sale price, but at only 6% of the data, it’s probably best to remove these.

ind = is.na(train$GarageYrBlt)
train = train[ind == FALSE,]
nas = train[,sapply(train, anyNA)]

Similarly, there are only 30 NAs for basement variabeles and masonry variables. We can scrap these too.

ind = is.na(train$BsmtExposure)
train = train[ind == FALSE,]
ind = is.na(train$MasVnrType)
train = train[ind == FALSE,]
nas = train[,sapply(train, anyNA)]

We can also get rid of the remaining rows where there are very few NAs

train = train[is.na(train$Electrical) == FALSE,]
train = train[is.na(train$BsmtFinType2) == FALSE,]
nas = train[,sapply(train, anyNA)]

Alleys

Now we have a handful of variables with NAs that may be useful to look at. The first, Alley; it may not have that much importance. We can plot alley’s against the outcome variable to see:

levels(train$Alley) = c(levels(train$Alley), "None")
train$Alley[is.na(train$Alley) == TRUE] = "None"
boxplot(train$SalePrice~train$Alley)

It looks like most of the cheaper properties have gravel or pavement alleys; the expensive properties do have them, but the outliers particularly account for no alleyway. My intuition tells me that we should binarise this variable instead of ditch it, because the outlier distribution may be useful information. This is our first example of feature engineering.

levels(train$Alley) = c("Yes", "Yes", "No")
boxplot(train$SalePrice~train$Alley)

Quality Measures

Pool Quality has far too many NAs for it to be useful at this point, as do Fence and MiscFeature (although miscellaneous features such as sheds and second garages are almost guaranteed to spike the price).

toRemove = c("PoolQC")
plot(factor(train$MiscFeature), train$SalePrice)

Tennis courts definitely increase the price. Let’s investigate MiscVal as it is a likely strong measure.

We can check if the outliers in the outcome variable are represented by these miscellaneous features:

plot(train$MiscVal,log(train$SalePrice))

Nope. This is likely not a useful measure.

Let’s ditch it, and instead use the binary measure suggested before.

toRemove = c(toRemove, "MiscVal")
levels(train$MiscFeature) = c("Y","Y", "Y", "Y", "N")
train$MiscFeature[is.na(train$MiscFeature)] = "N"

Fireplaces have quality scores, but they are not ultimately more useful than just having the number of fireplaces (I don’t assume people think a great deal about the state of the fireplace unless it’s in bad shape). Instead, we will just calculate a new variable for this aspect as a new feature, FPScore.

fp2 = NULL
fp2[train$FireplaceQu == "Ex"] = 5
fp2[train$FireplaceQu == "Gd"] = 4
fp2[train$FireplaceQu == "TA"] = 3
fp2[train$FireplaceQu == "Fa"] = 2
fp2[train$FireplaceQu == "Po"] = 1
fp2[is.na(train$FireplaceQu)] = 0
train$FPScore = (fp2)*(train$Fireplaces)
toRemove = c(toRemove, "FireplaceQu", "Fireplaces")
plot(train$FPScore,train$SalePrice)

cor(train$FPScore,train$SalePrice)
[1] 0.2141936

The best feature we can get for FPScore has a medium correlation with the outcome, 0.49, and is given by (quality)*(number of fireplaces).

Fence is an interesting variable. We can assume that good fences go with good homes, but more importantly, good fences come with certain types of neighbourhouds. Let’s investigate this:

levels(train$Fence) = c(levels(train$Fence), "NoFence")
train$Fence[is.na(train$Fence)] = "NoFence"
boxplot(train$SalePrice~train$Fence)

boxplot(train$SalePrice~train$Fence)$stats

However, since Fence is not likert-like, we can’t neessarily use it in a numerical manner. It will remain categorical.

The remaining variable with a bunch of NAs is LotFrontage, referring to the linear feet of street connected to the property.

summary(train$LotFrontage[1:train_index])
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
  21.00   59.00   69.00   70.05   80.00  313.00     259 
boxplot(train$LotFrontage[1:train_index])

This is a strictly numerical variable. Is it possible that homes can have no street directly connected to the property? Should NAs represent zero?

The problem that this causes is inflated zeros, which is a common problem in data analysis as it violates assumptions. Specifically, 244 homes may violate the assumptions, which is a lot. I think the best thing to do with this case is to replace the values with the mean.

train$LotFrontage[is.na(train$LotFrontage)] = 70.76
plot(train$LotFrontage, train$SalePrice)

cor(train$LotFrontage, train$SalePrice)
[1] 0.1540997

It’s a weak correlation, but we’ll keep it.

Subjective Scores

We’ve already seen how combining the number of fireplaces with the fireplace quality improves the correlation between this score and the sale price. Even if it is marginal, it’s useful in these types of problems. We’ll see if we can’t combine a few other variables, i.e., engineer some more features, that use subjective scores.

Subjective measures: OverallQual, OverallCond, ExterQual, ExterCond, BsmtQual, BsmtCond, BsmtExposure, BsmtFinType1, BsmtFinType2, HeatingQC, KitchenQual, Functional, FireplaceQu, GarageFinish, GarageQual, GarageCond, PoolQC, Fence

The first is the overall quality and condition.

cor(train$OverallCond, train$OverallQual)
[1] -0.09384734

Surprisingly, these two are not correlated.

gg = ggplot(data = train[1:train_index,])
gg + geom_raster(aes(OverallCond, OverallQual, fill = log(train$SalePrice[1:train_index])))

The plot seems to only slightly tend towards having higher expense for higher condition, but definitely higher price for higher quality. We can keep these seperate.

We can check the same for the external quality and condition. In this case, we definitely want to treat this as a pseudo continuous Likert scale.

ext1 = NULL
ext2 = NULL
ext1[train$ExterQual == "Ex"] = 5
ext1[train$ExterQual == "Gd"] = 4
ext1[train$ExterQual == "TA"] = 3
ext1[train$ExterQual == "Fa"] = 2
ext1[train$ExterQual == "Po"] = 1
ext1[is.na(train$ExterQual)] = 0
ext2[train$ExterCond == "Ex"] = 5
ext2[train$ExterCond == "Gd"] = 4
ext2[train$ExterCond == "TA"] = 3
ext2[train$ExterCond == "Fa"] = 2
ext2[train$ExterCond == "Po"] = 1
ext2[is.na(train$ExterCond)] = 0
cor(ext1, train$SalePrice)
[1] 0.2507717
cor(ext2, train$SalePrice)
[1] 0.001888145
cor(ext1, ext2)
[1] 0.02985199
train$ExtScore = (ext1)/(ext2)
cor(train$ExtScore, train$SalePrice)
[1] 0.201647
gg + geom_raster(aes(ExterCond, ExterQual, fill = log(train$SalePrice[1:train_index])))
toRemove = c(toRemove, "ExtScore")

There’s a higher correlation coefficient between External quality alone than there is between a combination of the two measures, so we keep them both seperate.

toRemove = c(toRemove, "GrgScore", "GarageQual", "GarageCond")

Fitting a sparse group lasso

cont_group = 1:length(cont)
for(i in 1:length(cont_group)){
  if(names(cont)[i] %in% Type_of_property){
    cont_group[i] = 1
  }else if(names(cont)[i] %in% Geographic_qualities){
    cont_group[i] = 2
  }else if(names(cont)[i] %in% Subjective_measures){
    cont_group[i] = 3
  }else if(names(cont)[i] %in% Physical_amenities){
    cont_group[i] = 4
  }else if(names(cont)[i] %in% Quantitative_measures){
    cont_group[i] = 5
  }else{
    cont_group[i] = 6
  }
}
cat_group = 1:length(cat)
for(i in 1:length(cat_group)){
  if(names(cat)[i] %in% Type_of_property){
    cat_group[i] = 1
  }else if(names(cat)[i] %in% Geographic_qualities){
    cat_group[i] = 2
  }else if(names(cat)[i] %in% Subjective_measures){
    cat_group[i] = 3
  }else if(names(cat)[i] %in% Physical_amenities){
    cat_group[i] = 4
  }else if(names(cat)[i] %in% Quantitative_measures){
    cat_group[i] = 5
  }else{
    cat_group[i] = 6
  }
}
all_cat_group = NULL
for(i in 1:length(cat_group)){
  temp = levels(cat[,i])%>%
    length()%>%
    rep(cat_group[i],.)
  all_cat_group = c(all_cat_group, temp)
}
groups = c(cont_group, all_cat_group)
dat = data.frame(cbind(cont,all_cat))
dat1 = dat[1:train_index,]
dat1 = dat1[complete.cases(dat1),]
zeros = as.vector(colSums(dat1))
zeros = zeros != 0
zeros[c(1,38)] = FALSE
groups = groups[zeros]
Y = log(dat1$SalePrice+0.00001)
X = dat1[,zeros]
data = list(x = X,y = Y)
sgl1 = SGL(data = data, index = groups, type = "linear")
